  "plot_summary": "The two new titles this month are closely related to the two from <i>last</i> month, being <i>Chamber of Darkness</i> and <i>Our Love Story</i>.&nbsp; The romance book, like its sister title, continued on until the end of 1975, for a total of 38 issues, so again, well done.&nbsp; The spooky/horror-themed book lasted for 8 issues before being rebranded, but I'll cover that when the time comes.\n\nThe <i>Mighty Marvel Checklist</i> erroneously lists [LINK:1969:SURFER_8|SURFER #8] as on sale (was actually #9).\n\n<i>Marvel Collector's Item Classics</i> (a reprint title) was rebranded as <i>Marvel's Greatest Comics</i> this month, starting with issue 23.&nbsp; For now, it retains its double-length size, but it will later shrink down to feature only Fantastic Four reprints (which is where I actually learned a lot about the earlier years of the FF when I first started buying Marvels in 1977).\n\nAlso interesting is how [LINK:1969:STRANGE_182|STRANGE #182] is listed as \"Still on Sale\" but no mention is made of <i>this</i> month's issue 183 (which would turn out to be the title's last).\n\nThis month's <i>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins</i> announces that the old MMMS club is being rolled into a \"parent organization named MARVELMANIA INTERNATIONAL.&nbsp; (This is Marvel's way of offloading the old club since they had no time to keep it functioning.)\n\nGil Kane's return is announced.&nbsp; He had been absent from Marvel for a couple of years, having previously worked on Captain America stories in <i>Tales of Suspense</i> and Hulk stories as part of <i>Tales to Astonish</i>.&nbsp; His new project, starting this very month, is Captain Marvel.&nbsp; Obviously, Gil Kane was a giant in the comics industry, having been there right at the beginning of the Silver Age with DC's <i>Green Lantern</i>, and his work is easily recognizable on so many of the Bronze Age Marvel comics to come.&nbsp; (I am happy to see him back, as I'd wondered where he went.)\n\nThis month's <i>Stan's Soapbox</i> announces that after years of continued stories, with the reading audience equally split on whether to keep them, they've decided to discontinue the practice.&nbsp; Some amount of time may pass before it kicks in, and it's not a hard and fast rule, but as a guideline, they decided that the other half of readers should get a turn to be heard:&nbsp; <i>but, by and large, we've given up our continued stories till further notice</i>!&nbsp; (We'll see how long this lasts, <i>heh</i>!&nbsp; I won't hold my breath!)",
