  "review_text": "This month featured 13 graded stories, all equally split into 13 physical issues, resulting in a final weighted grade of <b>6.12</b>, nearly an entire half point better than last month and one of the highest monthly grades we've had in a while (certainly the best of <i>this</i> year so far).\n\nThere were 10 books that punched in with at <i>least</i> a mid-grade rating this month, leaving only three below that, two of which dropped below reader level to boot.&nbsp; But what made this month's final rating that much more remarkable was the fact that it happened in the same month as the <i>Sub-Mariner</i> putting out its <i>worst issue ever</i>.\n\nThe absolute dead weight of [LINK:1969:SUB_18|SUB #18] (together with the very weak, but unsurprising, [LINK:1969:HULK_120|HULK #120] offering) threatened to derail everything, but as the days passed, and I proceeded through the books, I found so many highlights that happily offset the poorer ones, and <i>perhaps</i> for the first time, there were six in one month that got at least an upper-mid-grade rating, three of which were even <i>high</i>-grade.\n\nThe <i>Avengers</i> issue led the charge, with <i>Iron Man </i>and <i>X-Men</i> right behind.&nbsp; The struggling FF even came through this month with a solid rating, which was a nice surprise, and Spider-Man and Daredevil both held their own.&nbsp; Even the normally weak Doctor Strange held steady as part of his final issue.\n\nSo despite the dreadful Sub-Mariner book, the others really did shine for the most part, and I can only hope we get more months like this one!",
  "letters_page": "Introduction to Thermal Man, the Undying Ones, Death's Head, Torgo and Sauron (Karl Lykos)\n[INTRODUCTION_BEGIN]\nGalactus | Milestone: Origin Revealed\nThermal Man | villain | Milestone: First Appearance\nNotes | first | death | Kenneth Ward\nNotes | first | villain | Undying Ones\nNotes | Negative Zone (first appearance in this magazine)\nNotes | first | villain | Death's Head\nSauron | villain | Milestone: [first: as Sauron], [origin]\nNotes | first | Tanya Anderssen\n[INTRODUCTION_END]\n[HIGHLIGHTS_BEGIN]\nMadame Masque lowers her weapon, unable to shoot the man she was ordered to kill, having made her feel like a woman once again.\nThe Warriors Three versus the dreaded Thermal Man, everyone advised to \"Stay in your homes!\" (<i>Seriously</i>?&nbsp; Heh...)\nUltron can't face the final morality of... \"Thou shalt not kill.\"\nA final, and solid, send-off for Dr. Strange, whose solo adventures end - for now.\nSpider-Man uses his \"spider-sonic hearing\" to rid himself of the Human Torch's interference during his battle with the Lizard!\nKaren Page returns home to Vermont, only to meet...Death's Head!\nThe Thing...kidnapped...on a gangster planet...what could go <i>wrong</i>?\nThe alien Silver Surfer appeals to the Flying Dutchman's....<i>humanity</i>?\n\"Your eyes!&nbsp; <b>YOUR EYES..!!</b>\"&nbsp; (Need I say more?)\nBut <i>most importantly</i>, Jeff reviewed his <b>800<sup>th</sup></b> issue this month!\n[HIGHLIGHTS_END]",
  "ownership": "Looking ahead, Captain America (and Falcon) finishes things up with the Red Skull, with MODOK poised in the wings, Tony Stark faces off with Midas, Nick Fury swoops in for a final solo adventure, Thor and Galactus have a long chat, the Avengers meet an old foe from the past...or is that from the <i>future</i>?&nbsp; Meanwhile, the Silver Surfer...in <i>shades</i>?&nbsp; Both the Sub-Mariner and Spider-Man meet new foes, while Captain Marvel has to deal with an old one, Karen reaches for Daredevil's mask, the Thing prepares for the battle of his life, and the X-Men find they have more than Sauron to deal with!"
}